  "evidence_A": [
    "Shown: Reyner's seal. Shown: Reyner's yard. Still not shown: what the broken crown says about why it failed.",
    "That's the sharper version of what I was reaching for. A draw-roll that says 'so-and-so was cleared to pull this timber' doesn't finish the job if someone else could also claim equal clearance.",
    "A keystone break fixes the failure point — now we can go to that broken face and ask what it actually shows."
  ],
  "evidence_B": [
    "A green joint is like a loaf pulled from the oven raw: the fault is not that the baker never knew bread, but that the support was taken before the thing could stand.",
    "A bond is a purse opened against failure, clerk, not fingers on the timber.",
    "The yard is grounded; the hand remains unwritten."
  ],
  "reason": "Both transcripts trace the same derivation with equal rigor — they keep liability apart from causation, move from break-location to green-mortar cause to crowsfoot to Caudle yard to Oswin, and neither leaks raw predicates, variables, or proof-path notation. The difference is craft. B reads as the stronger didactic play: its stage directions are more alive, the sustained 'clerk' address gives the scene a relationship, and the tutor varies its teaching each turn with fresh concrete analogies (seal-as-mark, bond-as-purse, green-joint-as-raw-loaf, mark-as-road-sign, brand-as-threshold) that make why each piece of evidence matters especially legible, while its short declarative closes ('The yard is grounded; the hand remains unwritten') punctuate thinking rather than pad. A is excellent and equally sound, but its 'Shown:/Still not shown:' ledger recurs almost verbatim across five turns, which reads more mechanically and is the most proof-bookkeeping-flavored speech in either text. The two are even on dialogical acknowledgement (A's Turn 19 uptake is a genuine high point); B leads on flow, non-formalist variety, and readability."
}

