  "reason": "Both transcripts trace the identical inquiry (office vs. signing hand, the raven's-notch dusk-seal, the pass-law, Elian as keeper) and neither leaks raw formalism. A is more atmospheric and the cleanest on non-formalist speech, but its middle (turns 8-12) stalls into a holding pattern where the learner repeats the same two or three settled points, which reads as padding and weak phatic texture. B keeps stronger forward motion, clearer reader orientation via the maintained answerability/signing line, better-placed short acknowledgements, and notably more pedagogical traction - the learner anticipates what custody evidence would close the gap before it is produced. B's only weakness is that the repeated 'Rule, mark, holder' scaffold and the enumerated sufficiency conditions edge toward procedural exposure, but they remain in plain language. B wins four dimensions, ties one, and loses only non-formalist speech, so it is preferred at moderate strength."
